{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608695/1958012001/0351.xml":{"full_text":"Today: A Comic Strip Bonus of 7 Buck Rogers Installments Page B-13\nWEATHER FORECAST\nIncreasing cloudiness today. Cloudy with\nmixed sleet, snow and rain tonight, low 21.\nRain tomorrow. (Full report on Page A-2.)\nTemperatarea Today\nMidnight 22 g am... 25 n am.. .36\n2 am... 28 g am... 25 Noon ...38\n4 am... 28 10 am... 31 l p.m...40\n106th Year. No. 20. Phone BT. 3-5000\nLaw to Offset\nMallory Ruling\nHeld Needed\nHouse Unit Says\nIt Hampers Work\nOs Law Officers\nBy MIRIAM OTTENBERG\n\u25a0Ur aw> Writer\nChairman Willi* of a House\nJudiciary subcommittee said\ntoday he believes enough evi\ndence has been gathered to\nconvince the full committee\nthat the Supreme Court\u2019s Mal\nlory decision Is causing \u201cinsur\nmountable trouble to lav en\nforcement officers.\u201d\nThe Louisiana Democrat heads\nthe subcommittee studying the\nimpact of various Supreme\nCourt decisions of last year.!\nThe Mallory decision, which\nreversed a death penalty rape\nconviction, ruled out a confes\nsion because of a 74-hour\ndelay between arrest and ar\nraignment.\n\u201cAs long as a confession is\nfree and voluntary,\" Mr. WUlls\nsaid, \u201cthere should be no hide\nbound test that statement* must\nbe made within a certain num\nber of hours. Time should not\nbe the test of whether a con\nfession should be admitted.\"\nTime-Henered Test\nThe time-honored test. Mr.!\nWUlls went on. Is whether a\nconfession is voluntary. That,\nhe said, was the test applied\nIn the Federal court* before the\nMallory decision and the test\nthat still appUes In the State\ncourts.\nMr. Willis said he was \u201cvery\nmuch impressed\u201d with The\nStar\u2019s Sunday story on the Mal\nlory decision bringing out the\nsame point\u2014that In the State\ncourts Juries can hear voluntary\nconfession* that they are now\nbarred from hearing here and\nIn other Federal courts.\nThe subcommittee chairman,\nmaking his first statement on\nthe Mallory decision since the\nsubcommittee decided unani\nmously to press for remedial\nlegislation, said the subcommit\ntee will now move \u201cas\nwe possibly can to draft a bill\nfor the full committee.\n\u201cOur minds are made up.\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cthat law enforcement of\nficers cannot operate efficiently\nunder the Mallory decision. We\nthink we have enough now to\nprove to the full committee that\nlegislation is necessary and\nthat it should be along the\nlines we recommend.\"\nSeries of Hearing*\nThe subcommittee held a\nseries of hearings late last sum\nmer at which the majority of\nwitnesses from the District and\nthe States emphasized that if\npolice cannot bold suspects long\nenough to question them, inno\ncent men will face the stigma\nof criminal charges and men\nwho actually committed crimes\nwill slip through the fingers of\nlaw enforcement.\nA Btar review of six months\nof law enforcement here\nunder the Mallory decision\nbrought out that five Innocent\nmen were rushed to arraign\nment before police managed to\nclear them, two men convicted\nof first-degree murder saw\ntheir convictions reversed and\ncannot be tried again and the\nprosecutor has accepted pleas\nto lesser offenses in a number\nof cases where the Mallory is\nsue has been raised.\nLaos Chief in London\nLONDON. Jan. 20 UP).\u2014 Prince\nSouvanna Phouma, Prime Min\nister of Laos, flew to London\nfrom Montreal today for a two\nday visit to Britain. He is on\nhis way home after visits to\nParis. Washington and Ottawa.\nTO FIND\nTHE CAR\nYOU HAVE IN MIND\nSHOP\nSTAR\nCLASSIFIED\nIf you're in the market for\na new or used car don't\noverlook the many listings\nof top values in the auto\nmotive columns of Btar\nClassified today.\nFor Just the buy you've\nbeen looking for, at s price\ngeared to fit your budget,\nsee The Star first.\nWashington's preferred\nclassified medium by more\nthan 2 to 1 according to an\nAmerican Research Bureau\nsurvey.\nYdigoras Leads in Early\nGuatemalan Returns\nBy ARN.ILDO OTERO\nStef Stiff writer\nGUATEMALA. Jan. 20.\u2014Un\nofficial returns In Guatemala\u2019s\npreaidental election yesterday\nshowed Oen. Miguel Ydigoras\nPuentes of the Recovery Party\nahead.\nThe 82-year-old general again\nwon Guatemala city and Is re\nportedly ahead throughout the\nRepublic.\nShowing great signs of\nstrength In the unofficial count\nwhich was made by party\nworkers at headquarters here.\n!is Dr. Mario Mendes Mon\ntenegro, candidate of the Com\nmunist-Infiltrated Revolution\nary Party.\nIn third place is Col. Jose L.\nCrus Salazar, former Ambas\nsador to Washington and can\ndidate of the National Dem\nocratic Movement.\nRace Still Wide Opea\nThe race Is still wide open as\nvotes from faraway rural areas\nare now beginning to trickle In.\nBut the prospect of any of the\nthree front-running candidates\nobtaining an absolute majority\nhas become quite dim. This\nwould leave the selection of a\npresident up to Congress,\nscheduled to meet Thursday.\nYesterday\u2019s election* were\npeaceful and blessed with clear\nand sunny skies.\nToday, the electoral board is\nfuriously counting votes and\nrefusing to give any indication\nof how the voting is going.\nIt is feared that a report\nfrom the board at this time\nwould create the same violent\ndemonstrations which followed\nlast October's election.\nBy 10 o\u2019clock last night\nGuatemala city was complete\nly deserted. Only a small por\ntion of the large police and\nmilitary forces which have\nbeen on the streets for the pest\nfew days could be seen. Shops\non the city's main business dis\ntrict. particularly Sixth avenue\nwere securely locked with\nheavy steel covers over all show\nwindows.\nThe Plan Atalaya. a plan\ndesigned by the minister of de\nfense to quash a possible up\nrising. was not put into opera\ntion on election day.\nMovement to the polling\nSupreme Court Orders\nYugoslav Fugitive Held\nBy HOWARD LDI TKIN i\nOtar Stiff Writer\nThe Supreme Court today.\nIn the first case of its kind,\nordered a Yugoslav accused of\nbeing a war criminal to be\nremanded to the custody of a\nUnited States marshal in Cali\nfornia pending an extradition\nhearing.\nPlghtlng extradition Is An\ndrtja Artukovic. former minis\nter of the interior in the short\nlived government of Ante Pmla\nvie. Artukovic is accused by\nYugoslavia of ordering the kill\ning of some 200.000 persons In\nYugoslavia in 1941-42.\nPalavic became the boss of\nCroatia after the Nazi invasion\nin 1941. At the time, the prov\nince was declared to be an in\ndependent state, although un\nder Hitler domination, and its\ngovernment adopted ruthless\nNazi methods in attempting to\nestablish its authority.\nArtukovic. now a California\nresident, is badly wanted by the\nCommunist government of\nYugoslavia, acting through its\nconsul general in California.\nBranko Karadzole.\nFuchs Reaches Pole,\nWill Cross Antarctica\nWELLINGTON. New Zea\nland. Jan. 20 (A*).\u2014Dr. Vivian\nFuchs and hls British ground\nteam reached the South Pole\ntoday and announced they\nfirmly intend to press on to the\nother side of Antarctica.\nTough and fit despite their\ngrueling 57-day trek across\nmore than 900 miles of snow\nand Ice, the British explorer\nsaid he would go on as planned\nto Bcott Base, on McMurdo\nSound, for the first overland\ncrossing of the continent. But\nhe added that he had no idea\nwhen he would reach the end\nof his Journey.\nGreet 12 Britons\nRear Admiral Oeo\u2019-ge Dufek,\nUnited States Chief of Opera\ntion Deep Freeze, and Sir Ed\nmund Hillary, who reached the\npole overland from the opposite\ndirection 16 days earlier, were\non hand to greet the 12 Britons\nwho had brought their tractor\ntrain over 940 miles of terrain\nno man had set foot on before.\nSir Edmund and some other\nexperts had advised Dr. Fuchs\nagainst making the 1.200-mtle\nsecond Jeg of the trip because\nthey believe bad weather is in\nthe offing.\nThe party reached the United\nStates base at the Pole at 1:08\np.m. <8:08 p.m. EST Sunday)\nAbout 40 man came out to\nmeet them, slapping them on\nthe back, shaking their hands\nand excitedly congratulating\nthem.\n.Sir Edmund and Admiral\nWne Ibeniita\nV l WITH SUMPAY MORNING EDITION\nWASHINGTON, D. C\u201e MONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1968\u201440 PAGES\nV J I j\nGEN. YDIGORAS\nLeading Field\ni places yesterday was slow at\ni first but by mldmomlng long\nlines had formed throughout\nthe city.\nAccording to all unofficial\nIndications, the total voting\n/will not surpass last October's\nfigures\u201449o.ooo.\nIt has been said that many\nGuatemalans, satisfied with\nnone of the candidates, have\nstayed away from the polls. The\nvoting population of the re\npublic is more than a million.\nWill Abide by Vote\nj Provisional President Guil\nlermo Avendano was the first\nhigh official at the polls. He\ncast his ballot at La Aurora\nAirport. Two hours later Dr.\nMendes Montenegro went to\nthe polls at Colon Park amid\nloud cheers. He said: \u201cI have\nabsolute faith and optimism\nin the victory of the Revolu\ntionary Party.\u201d\nAt 11 am.. Oen. Ydigoras\nPuentes arrived at Francos y\nMonroy School to cast his bal\nlot. Said he: \u201cI\u2019ll get at least\n270.000 votes in this election\nIf I lose. I\u2019ll abide by the will\nof the people, who should decide\nthe destiny of the republic.\u201d\nA few minutes later. Col. Crus\nSalaaar voted at the Belem\nSchool for Oirls. saying \u201cthe\nforecast Is the same. I'm going\nto win because I have to win.\u201d\nAfter Artukovic s arrest last\nyear a district Judge freed him\non a writ of habeas corpus. The\naction was affirmed by the\nUnited States Court of Appeals.\nThe Supreme Court, dividing\n7 to 2. ordered that the writ be\ndischarged and that Artukovic\nbe taken into custody pending\na hearing on the Yugoslav\nclaim that he should be turned\nover under a treaty obligation\nIn freeing Artukovic. the\nlower courts cited a 1901 treaty\ncontaining a provision which\ndenies extradition for \u201coffenses\nof a political nature.\u201d\nThe lower courts held that\nby reason of his Job with the\nCroatian cabinet and the fac\ntional strife then rampant, the\noffenses were of a political na\nture.\nYugoslavia pointed out that\nresolutions of the United Na\ntions called for extradition of\nwar criminals if their guilt is\napparent.\nThe court's opinion was ex\npressed in one paragraph. Jua\ntices Black and Douglas dis\nsented but they gave no reasons.\ntfi\nLd\nDR. VIVIAN E. FUCHS\nGreeted by Hillary\n\u2014AP Wlrephoto\nDufek went out to meet the\nBritons a mile from the polar\nbaae. As the tractor train\npulled up with flags flying. Sir\nEdmund advanced to greet Dr.\nPucha.\nSurprised by Welcome\n\"Hello, Bunny.\u201d said the\nconqueror of Mount Everest,\nand the two men shook hands\nwarmly.\nDr. Fuchs appeared surprised\nby the welcoming party and\nbattery of cameras.\nSir Edmund and Admiral\nSee POLAR. Page A-4<\nEisenhower Set\nTo Open G.O.P.\nDrive Tonight\nPresident's Speech\nAt Chicago Dinner\nWill Be Televised\nPresident Eisenhower files to\nChicago today to kick off the\nRepublican campaign to try to\nwin control of the Senate and\nHouse this year with a nation\nally televised speech from Chi\ncago\u2019s International Amphithe\natre tonight.\nThe President Is scheduled to\nspeak for about 10 minutes near\nthe end of a 30-minute pro\ngram starting at 8:30 pm. over\nNBC television and radio net\nworks.\nHe will speak before a SIOO\n--plate dinner at Chicago, one\nof 44 fund-raising dinners ar\nranged by the Republicans in\n27 States and the District of\nColumbia tonight.\nDae Back Tmmitww\nMr. Eisenhower planned to\ntake off at about 1:46 pm. from\nWashington National Airport In\nhls private plane. Columbine\n111. Upon landing at Chicago,\nhe was to go by automobile di\nrectly to the Stockyards Inn.\nnear the amphitheatre. He will\nremain there overnight and fly\nback to Washington tomorrow.\nMrs. Eisenhower was flying to\nChicago with the President.\nAlso aboard the Columbine were\na small group of advisers and\nseveral Republican members of\nthe Illinois Congressional dele\ngation.\nThe cost of the Columbine's\nflight is being borne by the Re\npublican National Committee.\nThe United Republican din\nners tonight mark the fifth an\nniversary of President Eisen\nhower's first Inauguration on\nJanuary 20. 1863. The dinners\nare billed by the Republican\nNational Committee as a tribue\n.to five years of achievement\nunder the Eisenhower Admini\nstration and a \u201csalute to a Re\npublican Congress.\u201d\nCandidates Participate\nMany of tbs Republican\nmembers of the Senate and\nHouse who will be seeking re\nelection in November will be\ntaking part In the dinners\nacross the country.\nBesides Mr. Eisenhower, those\nspeaking on the half hour tele\nvision-radio program include\nVice President Nixon, Repub\nlican National Committee\nChairman Meade Alcorn: Miss\nBerths Adkins, assistant chair\nman of the National Committee;\nSenator Schoeppel. of Kansas,\nand Representative Simpson of\nPennsylvania. Chairman of the\nSenate and Congressional Re\npublican Campaign Commit\ntees.\nThose accompanying the\nPresident to Chicago Included\nhls personnel physician. MaJ.\nOen. Howard M. Snyder;\nJames C Hagerty. press sec\nretary. Robert Montgomery,\ntelevision adviser: Thomas E.\nStephens, local attorney and\nformer White House Appoint\nments Secretary who co-ordi\nnated arrangements for Mr.\nand Mrs. Mary Jane McCaflree.\nMrs. Elsenhower\u2019s secretary.\nSenator Dlrksen. Republican\nof Illinois, and Republican Na\ntional Committee Chairman\nAlcorn and Mrs. Alcorn and\nAssistant Budget Bureau Di\nrector Robert E. Merriam also\nwere aboard the Columbine as\nwere Illinois Republican Rep-j\nrcsentatlves Simpson. Arends.,\nChlperfleld. Allen. Springer, i\nMcVey and Vursell. j\nSleet, Snow, Rain\nDue by Tomorrow\nWith High of 40\nA mixture of sleet, snow and\nrain should hit the area out of\nthe west by tomorrow morning,\nthe Weather Bureau said today.\nThe Bureau did not try to\nestimate extent of the snow and\nsleet, but said rain may last\nfor quite a while tomorrow.\nHigher temperatures may j\nprevent an accumulation of\nsnow on the ground. A low of\n31 was forecast for tomorrow,\nrising to about 40.\nThere was a chance for\n\u2019\u2019quite a little snow\u201d in the\nmountain area* of Western\nMaryland, possibly extending\neastward through Northern\nMaryland and Delaware.\nHigh Radiation Found\nOver Central Pacific\nTOKYO. Jan. 20 OP).\u2014Un\nusual radioactivity was ob\nserved in the air over the Cen\ntral Pacific today by a Japanese\nnaval fleet on a training cruise\nto the Hawaiian Islands.\nThe flagship Harukaze re\nported that its Geiger counter 1\nrecorded radiation of 7,200 to\n10.000 counts per minute in the\nCentral Pacific 300 miles north\nwest of Wake Island.\nThe report expressed belief\nthe contaminated air may have\nfrom Siberia. I\nPresident Asks Steps\nTo Halt Business Sag\nwinnHHf\nK_\nWm v\n1 -a li\nmm\n\u00a7\u00a7f\nWELCOME ABOARD\u2014Chairman Johnson of the Senate Preparedness\nsubcommittee (right) welcomes Admiral Arleigh A. Burke, chief of\nnaval operations, on Capitol Hill today.\u2014AP Photo.\nPOST OFFICE\nDECREES END\nOF CUSPIDORS\nNow it Is official\u2014there'll\nbe no more cuspidors in\nUnited States post offices\nafter February 1.\nThe old friend of the to\nbacco chewer is headed for\noblivion \u201cin the interest of\nemploye welfare and mo\nrale. improved working and\nho u s ekeeping conditions\nand other attendant bene\nfits.\u201d\nSo said the Postal Bulle\ntin circulated to postal in\nstallations throughout the\ncountry.\nIt may come as a blow to\nsome customers out in Po\ndunk. but most Washing\nton area stations did away\nwith the shiny spittoons\nsome time ago. Without\nsentiment, postal officials\nwrote for those last sur\nvivors elsewhere:\n\u201cDisposal of this item\nshall be handled in the\nsame manner prescribed\nfor other surplus material.\u201d\niQuake Jolts Manila\nMANILA. Jan. 20 UP). A\ni strong earthquake Jolted Ma-\nI nila for one minute today,\nmaking tall concrete buildings\nsway. No damage or casualties\nwere reported.\nIndians in Klan Raid\nLinked to Lost Colony\nEvidence points to the possi-1\nblllty that the Lumbee Indians\nof North Carolina, Involved in\njthe week-end uprising against\nthe Ku Klux Klan, are de\nscended from the Lost Colony\nof Roanoke Island.\nStudenU of Indian ethnology\ndiscovered that aurnames of\nSheriff to Aik Isdictmool of KKK\nleader. fogs A-6\nmany of the Lumbers are the\nsame as some unusual names of\nthe first English settlers who\ndisappeared between 1587 and\n1501.\nBut history of the Lumbers\nhas been cloaked In much mys\ntery. and ethnologists of the\nSmithsonian Institution are\nstill digging for the truth.\nFlsht for Recognition\nThe tribe has been fighting\nfor recognition since anyone\ncan remember. The uncertain\nracial origin complicated things\nso much that in 1800 the group\nwas officially designated Croat\nans by the State Legislature.\nThe Croatans are linked\nclosely with the Loet Colony.\nFor when the settlers dlsap-\nthe sole clue was the\nSenators Query Navy\nOn Missiles and Subs\nDemocrats Would Push Bomber Output;\n4ir Force Plan to Hit Moon Reported\n8* the AuocilteO Preet\nThe Senate Preparedness Subcommittee is looking into\nthe adequacy of the Navy\u2019s submarine and missile programs\ntoday as it opens the Anal week of its current phase of\nbearings.\nAdmiral Arleigh A. Burke. Chief of Naval Operations,\nand Rear Admiral W. F. Raborn, who is supervising devel-\nopment of the Navy's Polaris\nmissile, were among witnesses\ntestifying behind closed doors.\nWhile Congress members\nargued variously that more\nmoney, more clearly defined\nj authority and more creative\nthinking are needed to spur\nUnited States defenses against\nRussian scientific gains, the\nweek end brought these devel\nopments:\n1. Senator Jackson. Democrat\nof Washington, said Senate!\nDemocrats are considering a\n$2 billion package proposal to\nincrease appropriations for\nlong-range Jet bombers, both\nIntermediate and medium-range\nballistic missiles, and missile\nfiring submarines.\n2. The magazine Aviation\nWeek predicted the Air Force\nwould attempt \u201cwithin the next\nlew months\u201d to send a payload\nrocket to the moon, and said\nthe Army will test nuclear ex\nplosions up to 50 miles above\nthe earth in experiments this\nsummer in the mld-Paciflc test\ning grounds. There was no of\nname \u201cCroatoan\u201d carved on a\ndoor post of the palisade. His\ntorians believe the settlers were\nabsorbed either by the Indians\nor mixed with Spanish settlers.\nAbout 1910 the Croat*ns of\nRobeson County, N. C., where\nmost of the 30,000 or so Lum\nbees now live, again went to\nthe legislature and officially be\ncame Cherokees.\nThis didn't work out well,\nfor the main stem Cherokees.\nliving in Western North Caro\nlina, gave the Robeson people\nno official status in their af\nfairs.\nNamed for River\nSo in 1933 another State\nlegislature action gave the\nLumbees their present official\nname, from a river flowing\nthrough Robeson County.\nOne group pulled stakes and\nmoved to Baltimore, settling a\ncolony In the eastern part of\nthe city now numbered at a\ncouple of thousand.\nOs the authorities who have\nstudied the people, one believes\nthey most resemble the Bioux.\nBut where the Lumbees started\nis a puzzle that matches the\nLost (f lony for mystery.\nHome Delivered: Si S 3 5 CENTS\nfleial confirmation of either re\nport.\n3. Dr. Ralph Swann, an Army\nrocket fuel expert at Hunts-\nI ville. Ala., disclosed in an m\n-1 terview that in laboratory tests.\nsolid fuels for rockets are show\ning almost as much thrust as\nliquid fuels. Four major scien\ntific breakthroughs in four\nyears have aided the solid fuel\ni development, opening the way\nto eventual factory production\nof ballistic missiles which can\nbe shipped ready to fire.\nSenator Jackson said the sen\natorial package proposal is\ni tentative and not yet cleared\nf by Democratic leaders. But he\nsaid it would call for additional\nappropriations which \"will cer\ni tainly be more than $1 billion\nand may run up to $2 billion.\u201d\nMuch of the actual spending\nj See MISSILES. Page A-4\nCongress Message\nIs Boon to Stocks\nNEW YORK. Jan 20 <>P!\u2014\nThe stock market advanced to\nday as President Eisenhower's\neconomic message was delivered\nto Congress.\nAfter early Irregularity the\nmarket firmed before the Presi\ndential report. It maintained its\ni advances after the message was\ndelivered.\nKey stocks gained fractions\ni to about sl, but there were\nsome rises running to $2 and $3.\nTrading was fairly active.\nI\nHouse Submits Bill\nOn Sobriety Test\nThe House today sent to con\nference a bill which would ad\nmit as testimony in District\ni courts chemical test* taken by\npersons charged with drunken\ndriving.\nThe House version differs in\nthree ways from the Senate\npassed bill.\nFirst, the House broadened\nI the applicability of the bill to\ncharges of negligent homicide\nand manslaughter as well as\nI drunken driving. The House\ni also would permit a breath test\nI In addition to chemical analy\ni sis of the blood or urine in\nfixing the degree of intoxiea\ntlon.\ni The third House amendment\nwas to make sure nobody could\n1 be forced to submit to chemical\ntests The Senate bill makes\ncompulsory.\nMetropolitan\nEdition\nNew York Markets, Page A-23\nInflationary\nPressures Hit\nIn Message\nBy GARNETT HORNER\nStir Stiff Writer\nPresident Elsenhower told\nCongress today that Govern\nment policies now are aimed\nat promoting business recovery\nwithout reviving inflationary\npressures.\nThe President's annual eco\nnomic report was cautiously\nT**t of President's Economic\nMessoge. Page A-4\noptimistic about expansion of\nthe Nation\u2019s economy over the\nlong run as in the near future.\nIt avoided any mention of\n\u201crecession\u201d for fear that word\nwould be unnecessarily disturb\ning. Instead it spoke of a \u201cmod\nerate decline\u201d in business ac\ntivity during the latter part of\n1957.\nThe President renewed warn\nings to business and labor that\nprice and wage increase out of\nline with costs and output\ncould thwart recovery hopes\nand invite Government con\ntrols.\nHe urged action by Congress\non a long list of recommen\ndations for legislation\u2014most\nof them already proposed in\nin one way or another\u2014to \u201cfos\nter a resumption of growth and\nbuild stronger foundations for\neconomic advances in the years\nahead.\u201d\nReasons for Confidence\n\u201cThere are good reasons for\nconfidence that a vigorous ex\npansion of our economy can bo\nsustained over the years,\u201d the\nPresident reported.\n\u201cAs we look ahead in 1958\nhe said, \u201cthere are grounds for\nexpecting that the decline in\nbusiness activity need not be\nprolonged and that economic\ngrowth can be resumed without\nextended interruption.\u201d\nHis report described 1957 as\na \u201cprosperous\u201d year, with em\nployment. personal income and\ntotal output of goods and ser\nvices all better than 1956. de\nspite \"a decline in the closing\nmonths.\u201d\nThe late 1957 change in eco\nnomic conditions called for ad\njustments in economic policies,\nthe President said.\n\u201cDuring much of the year.\"\nhe explained, the task of re\nstraining inflationary pressures\nwas paramount, and policies\nwere directed to this end.\n\u201cIn the closing months of the\nvear. and currently, the task has\nbeen to facilitate readjustments\nin the economy essential to the\nresumption of sustainable eco\nnomic growth, but to do so\nwithout reviving inflationary\npressures.\u201d\nReviews Lag in Growth\nHis report reviewed statistics\nmade public during recent days\nand weeks showing a lowered\ncurrent rate of economic\ngrowth. He said this \u201cwould\nclearly be unsatisfactory as a\ncontinuing condition.\"\nThe figures included: Per\nsonal income for 1957 aggre\ngating 5343 billion, up 5 per\ncent over 1956 but dipping $2 5\nbillion in the annual rate from\nNovember to December: total\noutput of goods and services,\n$434 billion for the year but\ndown in the fourth quarter to\nan annual rate of $433 billion\nfrom 3439 billion in the third\nquarter; employment of over\nContinued on Page A-4. Col 3\nWANT TO SAVE\nON INCOME TAX\u2019\nWANT TO SAVE MONEY?\nChonco art you cos, by reading\nAssociated Press Staff Writer G K.\nHodesfield's senes on income ta*et\nin Tbe Star. The first article appears\ntoday on Pogc 1-11.\nDEATH LIES in wait for Nick\nDons, television personality who\nthnvos on scandal and other peo\nple's troubles Sea t brand-now\nKtrry Drake police odventyre, be\nginning today on The Stor comic\npogos.\nA HENPECKED WORLD is whot\nJim lishops Aunt Alice li**\u00bb in.\nEor a look inside this world, so#\nPago I 11\nAN ENTERTAINING vocal ro\ncito.' of Bock's works by Jule end\nPeggy Zobowe at National Gollory\nof Art is reviewed on Page A-17.\nGuide for Readers\nAmuse'ts A 16-17 Feoture\nBusiness and Page I-II\nFinence A 22 23 Lost, Found A 3\nClassified I 6 10 Music A 17\nComics I-13-15 Obituary A-14\nCrossword 814 Soorts A-18 2)\nEditorial A 12 TV-Radio B 12\nEditonol Woman's\nArticles Al 3 Section B\u2019 5\nHove The Stor Delivered lo\nTout Home Doily and Sunday\nDial STerling 3-5000","height":"28537","width":"18391"}}
